# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ashrae
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The **Diamond District** is a commercial stretch containing a series of jewellers' shops.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] A notable, long-time anomaly of the district was the famous Gotham Book Mart, a bookstore, which was located at 41 West 47th Street from 1946 to 2004.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The move uptown started in the 1920s when rents in Maiden Lane began increasing drastically as finance and insurance companies moved into the Financial District.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The district grew in importance when Nazi Germany invaded the Netherlands and Belgium, forcing thousands of Orthodox Jews in the diamond business to flee Amsterdam and Antwerp and settle in New York City.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] Most of them remained after World War II, and remain a dominant influence in the Diamond District.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] By 1941, the Diamond Dealers Club—an exclusive club that acts as a de facto diamond exchange and has its own synagogue—officially made the move up to midtown as well.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The area is one of the global hubs of the diamond business, as well as the premier center for jewelry shopping in the city.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] It is one of the largest diamond and jewelry districts in the United States, along with Jewelers' Row, Philadelphia and Los Angeles's Jewelry District, and it is the second oldest surviving jewelry district in the United States after Jewelers' Row in Philadelphia.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] Total receipts for the value of a single day's trade on the block average $400 million.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] An estimated 90% of diamonds in the United States enter through New York.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] There were some 3,500 independent businesses (cutting, polishing and sales) in the district in 2019.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] According to other sources, the district was home to more than 2,600 businesses in 2020, a majority of them were on the same block, many shop owners and managers of the district were Orthodox Jews.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The wholesale business made up most of the $24.6 billion in annual sales in 2019.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The industry employed 33,000 people, still predominantly Jews.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] Most businesses are located in booths at one of the 25 "exchanges" in the district.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] Commission based hawkers are a common sight and they usually solicit business for stores located on the street level.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] According to *The New York Times*, the Diamond District has maintained a thriving, bazaarlike marketplace since the 1920s.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] Many deals are finalized by a simple, traditional blessing (**mazel und brucha**, which mean "luck and blessing" in Yiddish) and handshake.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] Retailers with shops line the streets outside.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] At 50 West 47th Street is the Gemological Institute of America which trains gem dealers.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] One distinguishing figure of the district is the diamond-motif street lights illuminating the corners.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The NYC Diamond District holds three prominent trade interconnected buildings: the 580 Fifth Avenue Exchange, the DDC, Diamond Dealers Club, and the International Gem Tower.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] It is close to other landmarks such as Rockefeller Center and Radio City Music Hall.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The New York City Subway's 47th–50th Streets – Rockefeller Center station on the IND Sixth Avenue Line offers service on the B, D, F, <F>, and M services.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] An underground concourse connects the station with the buildings of Rockefeller Center.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] The 49th Street station on the BMT Broadway Line offers service on the N, Q, R, and W trains, and is accessible via a part-time booth at Seventh Avenue and 47th Street at the south end of the station.
[src:ashrae/47th-street-manhattan] Several New York City Bus routes running along north-south avenues stop near the street.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] An **absorption-compression heat pump** (**ACHP**) is a device that integrate an electric compressor in an absorption heat pump.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In some cases this is obtained by combining a vapor-compression heat pump and an absorption heat pump.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] It is also referred to as a hybrid heat pump which is however a broader field.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Thanks to this integration, the device can obtain cooling and heating effects using both thermal and electrical energy sources.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This type of systems is well coupled with cogeneration systems where both heat and electricity are produced.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Depending on the configuration, the system can maximize heating and cooling production from a given amount of fuel, or can improve the temperature (hence the quality) of waste heat from other processes.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This second use is the most studied one and has been applied to several industrial applications.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The first absorption-compression heat pump cycle concept was patented by Osenbrück.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Little research on it was done in the following years.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] in the 70s, the energy saving potential of the cycle grew in interest and there was a rapid increase in research activities in the field.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In this period several experimental plants were built and in 1997, Groll summarized this activities in its review where he identified more than 40 studies.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] At that time, considerable work was still needed before the ACHP could become commercially available.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Nordtvedt studied the cycle in his doctoral thesis and his studies ended up in the construction, in 2011, of the first commercial application in the Norwegian Food Industry.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] After this, several units have been installed for commercial use in various high temperature industrial applications.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantage with respect to compression heat pump is that the compression-absorption heat pumps allow the heat to be transfer with a temperature glide.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The compression heat pump uses a single pure working fluid, hence exchanges heat at a constant temperature.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption-compression heat pump uses instead a binary mixture where the condensation and evaporation occur with a temperature glide.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This property increases the efficiency of the heat transfer when the heat source also has a significant temperature glide, which is the typical condition found when dealing with waste heat recovery.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Being a hybrid solution that can exploit both heat and mechanical/electric energy sources, the device can be perfectly coupled with cogeneration units to produce heating and cooling at very high efficiencies.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Moreover, it makes the system more flexible, allowing the optimization of the mix of electricity and thermal energy.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Their availability vary in fact along the day and the year.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Therefore the flexibility allow to reduce the operating costs.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main drawback of this technology is that, to achieve good performances, they typically need to employ ammonia, which is very toxic and flammable.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This drawback resulted in the fact that these applications remained limited to the industrial sector, where it is more practical dealing with dangerous fluids.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most studied configuration is the so-called *compression heat pump with solution cycle* (CHPS) or *compression resorption heat pump* (CRHP), where the compressor is in parallel to the electric pump located between the absorber and the desorber.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration is used to increase the temperature of waste heat since it allow high absorption temperature at lower pressure than compression heat pumps.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Another possible configuration for the absorption compression heat pump is obtained from the combination of a gas-driven absorption heat pump (GAHP) with a vapor-compression heat pump.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This configuration arises from the consideration that both cycles have in common a condenser, a lamination valve, and an evaporator.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main difference between the two is in the compression phase: where the compression heat pump uses an electric compressor, the gas-driven absorption heat pump uses a thermal compressor.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The ACHP is obtained by combining the components that are in common and using the electric and thermal compressor in parallel or in series.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Compression heat pumps use only a single fluid which is a refrigerant.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In contrast, absorption heat pump requires two fluids, a refrigerant and an absorbent able to absorb it.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] By combining the two devices, proper refrigerant absorbent pairs compatible with both the cycles are needed.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] There is a wide choice of refrigerants available for compression heat pumps.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorption cycle is the one limiting the choice of the refrigerant.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The most common refrigerants for absorption systems are ammonia and water.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Both are good for combined absorption-compression heat pumps.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ammonia has an exceptionally good solubility in water.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This is an important aspect that increases the performance and decreases the size of the device.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] However, its high toxicity and flammability reduces its attractiveness.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Water is a very attractive refrigerant because it is abundant, non-toxic, non-flammable and highly soluble in lithium bromide (LiBr).
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main issue with water is that, at the typical heat pump evaporator pressures, it freezes at 0 °C.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] This makes water unsuitable for the applications where the cold sink goes below 0 °C, which is the typical winter operating condition of an air source heat pump.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The absorbent and refrigerant are strictly related to each other.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that ammonia is used as refrigerant, the most common absorbent is water.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] In the case that water is used as refrigerant, as previously mentioned, the absorbent is usually LiBr.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] Ionic liquids have also been proposed as good absorbents, specially for water as refrigerant.
[src:ashrae/absorption-compression-heat-pump] The main advantages of these salts is that they can be used under the conditions at which LiBr solution runs the risk of crystallization and they are less corrosive.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:ashrae/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The informative appendices are not part of the standard, but provide additional information about terms and methods described within the standard, as well as a bibliography, and a description of the addenda incorporated from the previous version in the current version.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] As described within the standard: "The purpose of the standard is to specify the combinations of indoor thermal environmental factors and personal factors that will produce thermal environmental conditions acceptable to a majority of the occupants within the space".
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The standard addresses the four primary environmental factors (temperature, thermal radiation, humidity, and air speed) and two personal factors (activity and clothing) that affect thermal comfort.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Adaptive model is a model that relates indoor design temperatures or acceptable temperature ranges to outdoor meteorological or climatological parameters.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Thermal comfort is the condition of mind that expresses satisfaction with the thermal environment and is assessed by subjective evaluation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] A occupant-controlled naturally conditioned space is where the thermal conditions of the space are primarily regulated by occupant-controlled openings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Clothing insulation is the resistance to sensible heat transfer provided by a clothing ensemble (expressed in units of clo, which is a unit to quantify the insulation provided by garments and clothing ensembles.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Exceedance hour is the number of occupied hours within a defined time period in which the environmental conditions in an occupied space are outside the comfort zone.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The graphic method utilizes an overlay on a psychrometric chart to indicate the operative temperatures and humidity at which thermal comfort is achieved in the winter (1.0 *clo*) and summer (0.5 *clo*).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] It is based on the Predicted Mean Vote (PMV) model.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The graphic comfort zone model is limited in applicability to conditions when the metabolic rate of occupants is 1.0-1.3 met and the humidity ratio is below 0.012 kg H2O/kg dry air (0.012 lb H2O/lb dry air).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] If these requirements are met and the environmental conditions inside the building fall within the indicated ranges, then compliance is achieved.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For humidity ratios above 0.012 kg H2O/kg dry air (0.012 lb H2O/lb dry air), or for metabolic rates up to 2.0 met, the analytical model must be used to determine thermal comfort sensation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Also based on the PMV model, this method uses tools such as the ASHRAE Thermal Comfort Tool or the online CBE Thermal Comfort Tool for ASHRAE 55 to evaluate thermal comfort.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Users provide operative temperature (or air temperature and mean radiant temperature), air speed, humidity, metabolic rate, and clothing insulation value, and the tool evaluates predicted thermal sensation on a scale from -3 (cold) to +3 (hot).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Compliance is achieved if the conditions provide thermal neutrality, measured as falling between -0.5 and +0.5 on the PMV scale.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The section sets provisions for increasing the upper air temperature limit at elevated air speeds above 0.20 m/s (39 ft/min).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The methodology is based on the SET (Standard Effective Temperature) model, which provides a way to assign an effective temperature (at a standard metabolic rate, and clothing insulation values) to compare thermal sensations experienced at a range of thermal conditions.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The upper limit of air speed is based on whether occupants have local control or not.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] To evaluate compliance, the ASHRAE Thermal Comfort Tool may be used, or a computer model validated against the code provided in Informative Appendix D of the standard.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Radiant temperature asymmetry between ceiling and floor, and air and walls must be limited to reduce discomfort.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] To reduce draft risk at temperatures below 22.5 °C (72.5 °F), air speed due to the HVAC system must be 0.15 m/s (30 ft/min) or below.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The vertical air temperature difference between ankle and head is limited to 3 °C (5.4 °F) for seated occupants and 4 °C (7.2 °F) for standing occupants.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] If occupants' feet will be in contact with the floor, the temperature must be 19–29 °C (66–84 °F).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] When occupants do not have control over the cyclical variation or drifts in indoor environmental conditions, the conditions within this section must be met.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Operative temperatures may not fluctuate more than 1.1 °C (2.0 °F) within 15 minutes, nor change more than 2.2 °C (4.0 °F) within 1 hour.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] This method, also known as the adaptive comfort model, is applicable in buildings without mechanical cooling (and no operating heating system) where occupants' met rates are 1.0-1.3 met and their clothing levels are 0.5-1.0 *clo*.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For this model the standard provides a graph of acceptable indoor temperature limits at prevailing mean outdoor temperatures (a mean of the daily mean outdoor temperatures of the previous 7–30 days).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] An accompanying table lists provisions for higher operative temperatures at air speeds above 0.3 m/s (59 ft/min) and up to 1.2 m/s (240 ft/min).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The graph is valid for prevailing mean temperatures between 10 and 33.5 °C (50.0 and 92.3 °F).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] It provides 80% and 90% acceptability ranges, indicating the percentage of occupants expected to be comfortable at the indicated indoor and prevailing mean outdoor temperatures.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] This section of the standard is applicable for the design of buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] All of the building systems must be designed to maintain the occupied spaces at the indoor conditions specified by one of the described evaluation methods at design conditions.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The systems must be able to maintain these conditions within the expected range of indoor and outdoor operating conditions.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Although the evaluation of comfort in existing buildings is not mandatory in ASHRAE 55, it can be used as a guideline when required by other standards.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Occupant surveys and environmental measurements are primarily used for evaluation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] When the building automation system is added, the relevant characteristics must be described.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Indoor thermal comfort can be determined from the responses of the occupant survey.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Surveys must cover either the entire occupancy or a sample of it.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] When soliciting feedback from over 45 occupants, a minimum 35% response rate is required.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For sample sizes between 20 and 45, at least 15 responses are necessary, while surveys directed at fewer than 20 occupants need an 80% response rate to ensure reliability.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Generally, the scale in thermal satisfaction surveys must end with options "very dissatisfied" and "very satisfied." An open-ended response to document reasons for dissatisfaction should also be provided.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] "Cooler", "without change" and "warmer" are used for thermal preference questions.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For mechanically conditioned spaces, the PMV-based comfort zone has to be determined, which includes measuring and recording the metabolic activity and clothing insulation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The comfort zone boundaries must be adjusted to the air movements, and the zone conditions should be adjusted to avoid local thermal discomfort.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For occupant-controlled naturally conditioned space, the adaptive model shall be used to determine the thermal comfort boundaries.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For such spaces, the indoor and outdoor air temperature and mean radiant temperature and the air speed need to be measured.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Air temperature and speed must be measured at heights of 0.1 m, 0.6 m, and 1.1 m for seated occupants; 0.1 m, 1.1 m, and 1.7 m for standing occupants; and at the mean height of the body for horizontal occupants.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Operative temperature or PMV should be calculated at 0.6 m for seated occupants, 1.1 m for standing occupants, and the mean height of the body for horizontal occupants.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Local discomfort caused by floor temperature and radiant temperature asymmetry should be measured at the floor surface and at the occupants' locations, respectively.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The standard suggests that the time of measurements should last two or more hours long, and it should also be a representative time of the year for this specific building.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Measuring time step should be no more than five minutes for air temperature, mean radiant temperature, and humidity, and no more than three minutes for the air speed.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] In order to achieve acceptable results, the standard also suggests the minimum equipment accuracy based the current industry standard.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] When measuring environmental data from the Building Automation System, sensor placement must align with the recommended criteria for physical measurements.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Temperature sensors should achieve an accuracy of ±0.5 °C (±1 °F) and humidity sensors ±5% relative humidity.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The trending capabilities require data to be recorded at intervals of no more than 15 minutes, spanning a minimum of 30 days.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Concurrent data, such as equipment status and supply/return air temperatures, should also be collected for a comprehensive analysis.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] To evaluate the probability of satisfaction from satisfaction surveys, the standard suggests dividing the number of the votes falling between "just satisfied" and "very satisfied" by the total number of votes in that questions.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The answers of open-ended questions from "very dissatisfied" occupants should be documented for later analysis.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For point-in-time surveys, the comfort evaluation shall be performed by dividing the number of votes between -1 and +3 by the total number of votes.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] One has to keep in mind that the results from point-in-time surveys are only effective during the time when the surveys were solicited.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The measured results should be evaluated against the adjusted comfort zone for the specific building.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] There are two cases when evaluating thermal comfort: at a specific time or over a period of time.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For a mechanically conditioned space at an instance in time, the PMV and SET model shall be used to establish the comfort zone, and the local thermal discomfort shall be evaluated against the limit posed this standard as well.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For occupant-controlled naturally conditioned spaces, the measured results shall be check with the comfort zone established by adaptive model.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] To evaluate the thermal comfort over a period of time in a mechanically conditioned space, the exceedance hours are the sum of all the hours when the absolute value of PMV is greater than 0.5.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] For an occupant-controlled naturally conditioned space, the exceedance hours are the sum of hours when the operative temperature falls outside of the lower and upper boundaries of the comfort zone.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Metabolic rate is the rate of transformation of chemical energy into heat and mechanical work by metabolic activities of an individual.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] It is defined as per unit of skin surface area which equals to 58.2 W/m2 (18.4 Btu/h·ft2).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] This is the energy produced from a unit skin surface area of an average person seated at rest.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] When the duration of an activity is equal or less than one hour, one can use a time-weighted metabolic rate.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] As metabolic rates increase over 1.0 met, the evaporation of the sweat becomes an increasingly important factor, and the PMV method does not fully account for this factor.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Clothing insulation refers to the heat transfer of the entire body, which includes the uncovered parts, such as hands and heads.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] There is a variety of means to determine the insulation provided by clothing.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Accurate data from the measurement using thermal manikins is acceptable.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] When such measurement is not feasible, this standard provides four methods to determine the clothing insulation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] It is also specified that the methods provided by this standard are no longer valid when the clothing insulation exceed 1.5 *clo*.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] And it is also not valid when occupants wear clothing that is highly impermeable to moisture transport.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The first method is the least accurate, according to *ANSI/ASHRAE Standard 55*, and the accuracy increases in order of the methods.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] First, one can estimate the clothing insulation from the table provided in section five.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] If the clothing ensemble in question reasonably matches the clothing ensemble in the table, the indicated value can be used.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The second method is to add or subtract individual garment clo value to achieve the clothing ensemble in question.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Section five of the *ANSI/ASHRAE Standard 55* provides a table with clothing insulation of a variety of individual garments.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] This table can be used together with the previous one, so that one can add or subtract the clothing ensemble from the *clo* value of each garment.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The third method is to add all the *clo* value of each garment to match the clothing ensemble in question.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The fourth method described in *ANSI/ASHRAE Standard 55* can be used to determine the clothing insulation in mechanically conditioned spaces.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] This method is based on the concept that when occupants choose their clothing according to their environment, the outdoor environment is more influential than the indoor one.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] There is a figure in the section five of the standard which predicts the representative clothing insulation of the occupants as a function of the average outdoor air temperature at 06:00 am.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] There is a function to determine the representative clothing insulation at each segment.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] One can also take into account the posture of the occupants.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] So far, all the clothing insulation value can be used when the occupant is standing.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] When occupant is sitting, one has to realize the insulation effect of the chair, and the decrease of insulation due to compression of the air in the clothing.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] If the occupant is moving, it also affects the insulation value of clothing.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] In general, body motion decreases the clothing insulation by pumping air through clothing.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] *ANSI/ASHRAE Standard 55* recognizes that this effect varies largely depending on the nature of the movements and the nature clothing, such as how tight the clothing is.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Thus, it only provides an approximation of the clothing insulation value of a moving person.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] This approximation is an equation that relates the clothing insulation with the metabolic rate.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] And this equation is only valid when the metabolic rate is between 1.2 and 2.0.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] In 1992 the standard was updated with more extensive information on measurement protocols and an expanded definitions section.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] In 2004 the standard underwent significant changes with the addition of two thermal comfort models: the PMV/PPD model and the adaptive comfort model.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] In 2010 the standard included the following changes.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] It re-introduced the Standard Effective Temperature (SET) as a method to calculate the cooling effect of air movement.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] It also added a general satisfaction survey to section 7 intended to evaluate general thermal comfort in an occupied space, bringing the standard in line with current survey-based post-occupancy evaluation (POE) practices.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] In 2013 the body of the standard was rewritten in mandatory language, with informative language moved from the body of the standard to informative appendices.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The applicability of the cooling effect of air movement was expanded to apply to naturally conditioned spaces.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] Section 7 underwent major revisions for measuring thermal comfort in existing spaces including procedures for physical measurements and survey methods, and how to evaluate and report results.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] The last major change concerns measuring air speed and air temperature experienced by the occupant, which now must be an average across three heights and over a period of time.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-55] It was replaced by 2023 edition, which incorporated previous addenda to 2020 edition with renewed focus on organizational clarity.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Within the sections of the standard, there are some variations to this.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Some sections have mandatory provisions, simplified approaches, or trade-off opportunities.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In the performance approach, a baseline **energy cost budget** (**ECB**) is established, based on the building size and program.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] This *baseline ECB* is established using building performance simulation to model a building with the same size and program as the project building, built according to the prescriptive requirements of ASHRAE 90.1 (sections 5-10).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The ECB is expressed in units of dollars.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] A building performance simulation is then performed on the *proposed* building design.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The *proposed* energy cost budget must be less than or equal to the *baseline* energy cost budget to achieve compliance.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The performance approach is also used to demonstrate design energy efficiency, often expressed as *percent better than ASHRAE Standard 90.1*.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Building designs will state their performance as "40% better than ASHRAE 90.1-2007" or "20% better than ASHRAE 90.1-2010".
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Percent improvement over ASHRAE 90.1 is the basis for awarding energy points within the LEED rating system.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Many states apply ASHRAE 90.1 to buildings being constructed or under renovation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Most states apply the standard or equivalent standards for all commercial buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Others apply the standard or equivalent standards for all government buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] There are some states that use other energy conservation standards for all commercial buildings and some other states that use a combination of the ASHRAE 90.1 standard for all government buildings and use other energy conservation standards for their commercial buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] A few states do not apply any energy conservation standards for their government and commercial buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Current status of adoption into energy codes is tracked by the Building Codes Assistance Project.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The California Energy Code (CCR Title 24 Part 6) has a very similar structure and requirements.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] ASHRAE 90.1 is also an industry standard referenced by the USGBC in the LEED building certification program.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] It is frequently used as a baseline for comparison during energy retrofit projects or any project that employs building performance simulation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Outside the US, India's Energy Conservation Building Code, has a similar form and scope to ASHRAE 90.1.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Development of Standard 90 began in the aftermath of the 1970s energy crisis.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Kirkwood made the ASHRAE theme of 1973 "Optimum Energy Utilization Through Technology".
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] At ASHRAE's winter meeting in Los Angeles in February 1974, the National Bureau of Standards (NBS) presented their early developments of a building energy standard to 200 ASHRAE meeting participants.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] NBS and the National Conference of States on Building Codes and Standards (NCSBCS) offered to turn development of the standard over to ASHRAE, and ASHRAE accepted.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The development of the proposed standard, Standard 90P, was completed in less than six months.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] ASHRAE enlisted representatives from the American Institute of Architects (AIA), Illuminating Engineering Society (IES), Mechanical Contractors Association of America (MCAA), Air Conditioning and Refrigeration Institute (ARI), and the Electrical Energy Association (EEA).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] A draft of the standard was issued on June 21, 1974, to 5,000 industry stakeholders for public review.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Comments were received, revisions were made, and the initial version was issued as ASHRAE Standard 90-1975 on January 14, 1975.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In 2004 the ASHRAE 90.1 standard applied to buildings, the building envelope, and majority of mechanical and lighting systems in the building.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] New buildings being constructed and the systems that run the new buildings would be covered by the standard.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The standard would also apply to additions to existing buildings and their systems as well as alterations to an existing buildings system.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] For ASHRAE 90.1 standard to apply to the building envelope the building will need to be heated by a heating system that has an output capacity greater than 3.4 btu/h-ft2 or be cooled by a cooling system that has an output capacity greater than 5 btu/h-ft2.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In 2007 the updated version of the ASHRAE 90.1 covers many sections of a building which include building envelope, HVAC, hot water, and lighting.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The building envelope has to be categorized into three different categories of conditioned space which are (a) nonresidential conditioned space, (b) residential conditioned space, and (c) semiheated space.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Each one has different requirements to meet.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] There are also mandatory provisions that building envelopes have to abide by which are insulation, fenestration and doors, and air leakage.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The requirements for these provisions are in the ASHRAE 90.1 manual and have many requirements for each.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Each section of the building envelope, Roof, Walls, and Floor have different requirements for each of the mandatory provisions.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The HVAC system has many different requirements that have to be met.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] This is because there are many types of HVAC systems each with different requirements.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The HVAC section has the most requirements because there are so many different types of systems.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] There are systems that can not be used and things that systems must have to meet the requirements.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] ASHRAE 90.1 document has multiple tables that give minimum efficiency requirements for each system.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Hot water systems must go through a load calculation before they are installed.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Each system must meet the manufacturer's sizing guidelines.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Each system must also have equipment that meets the minimum efficiency that is in a table in the ASHRAE 90.1 document.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The pipes that hold the hot water need to be insulated and there are certain insulation requirements for each system type and piping material.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] There are many controls that hot water systems need and each control has a different requirement.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] These include are temperature controls, temperature maintenance controls, outlet temperature controls, and circulation pump controls.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] There are also requirements for pool heaters, pool covers, and heat traps for heated pools.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] If new lights are installed or replaced in any building space, with a few exceptions, they must abide by the Lighting Power Density requirements.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Lighting also has many requirements to follow, which includes the prescriptive requirements to determine the quantity of lights for the building.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] There are also interior lighting controls that need to be installed for buildings larger than 5000 sq. ft.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] There are also many requirements on lighting that include exit signs and exterior lights.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In the 2010 edition of ASHRAE 90.1, many changes were made, including definitions, tables, and sections.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Energy savings compared to 90.1-2004 were approximately 25 percent including plug loads and approximately 31 percent excluding plug loads.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] DOE issued a positive determination and notified states that they should adopt 90.1-2010 or a code that DOE accepts as equivalent by October 2013.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The scope was expanded to include defined industrial processes, which in the 2010 edition includes only economizers for data centers.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Changes to Building Envelope include skylights, solar reflectance, thermal emittance, air barriers, and solar orientation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Minimum efficiency requirements for many types of HVAC equipment were revised.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Other revisions affect the maximum fan power limits, pump head calculation, chilled water pipe sizing, radiant panel insulation, single-zone VAV, and supply air temperature reset.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Energy recovery is required for many more HVAC systems.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Several reheat exceptions were eliminated or modified.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Restrictions were placed on overhead air heating.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Economizer requirements were added for more climate zones and smaller systems.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Class A is now required for all duct sealing.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In the 2013 edition several updates were made to the building envelope, lighting and mechanical sections of the standard.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] With each new edition of ANSI/ASHRAE/IES Standard 90.1, DOE is required by statute to issue a determination as to whether the updated edition will improve energy efficiency in commercial buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] DOE issued a positive determination stating that Standard 90.1-2013 would achieve greater energy efficiency in buildings subject to that code.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Compared to 90.1-2010, 90.1-2013 is expected to save approximately 8.7% in energy cost, 8.5% in source energy and 6.7% in site energy.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Updates to the building envelope section of 90.1-2013 include changes to the prescriptive opaque envelope and fenestration performance requirements in several climate zones and modifications to the fenestration orientation requirements.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Updates to the lighting section include modified lighting power allowance requirement for interior and exterior lights; and modifications to lighting control requirements based on daylighting and occupancy sensors.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In the mechanical section, minimum efficiency requirements for many types of HVAC equipment are revised.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In addition new requirements for commercial refrigerators, freezers and refrigeration equipment, heating systems in vestibules and modifications for optimum start requirement for DDC systems, system size and outdoor air thresholds for energy recovery and occupancy threshold for DCV are included.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The 2016 edition of ASHRAE 90.1 contains several important changes to reduce energy consumption in commercial buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Significant changes include a new compliance path known as Performance Rating method included in Appendix G of the standards document, addition of two new weather zones, a new document format and new technical requirements for building envelope, lighting and mechanical systems.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] DOE issued a positive determination that Standard 90.1-2016 would achieve greater energy efficiency in buildings subject to the code and notified states that they should adopt 90.1-2016 or a code that DOE accepts as equivalent by February 2020.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Compared to 90.1-2013, 90.1-2016 is expected to save approximately 8.2% in energy cost, 7.9% in source energy and 6.7% in site energy.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Updates under lighting section include modified lighting power allowance requirement for interior and exterior lights; light source efficacy requirements for dwelling units and modifications to lighting control requirements.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Under the mechanical section modifications include updates to the chilled water plant metering, DOAS, elevator efficiency, economizer fault detection and diagnostics.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In addition to the energy cost budget method Appendix G is allowed as a new compliance path.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The Appendix G baseline is fixed at a specific level allowing buildings from any code version to be compared against a stable baseline using a new metric called building performance factor (BPF).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] The BPF is based on climate zone and building type allowing for greater flexibility in compliance modeling.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In the 2019 edition of ASHRAE 90.1, various modifications and clarifications were made to improve internal consistency.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Significant changes include: new commissioning requirements per ASHRAE/IES Standard 202; and updates to building Envelope, Lighting, Mechanical, Energy Cost Budget, Performance Rating Method sections.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Updates to the building envelope section include revision to exceptions for air leakage requirements and SHGC, U-factor revisions for fenestrations.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Under the lighting section the lighting power density allowance is modified for the Space-by-Space and Building Area methods.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] A new simplified lighting method is added for office and retail buildings up to 25,000 square feet (2,300 m2).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Additionally, lighting control requirements for parking garages and exceptions for controls in daylit areas are included.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] Under Section 11, Energy Cost Budget (ECB) Method baseline requirement for on-site electricity generation systems are added.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-90] In addition under both compliance paths updated language for treatment of renewables and lighting modeling are included.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] The **ASHRAE Handbook** is the four-volume flagship publication of the nonprofit technical organization **ASHRAE** (**American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers**).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] This Handbook is considered the most comprehensive and authoritative repository of practical knowledge on the various topics that form the field of heating, ventilation, air-conditioning, and refrigeration (HVAC&R).
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] The four volumes are *Fundamentals*, *Refrigeration*, *HVAC Applications* ("Applications"), and *HVAC Systems and Equipment* ("Systems and Equipment").
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] Members of ASHRAE receive the current volume, in both print and CD-ROM form, each year as a basic membership benefit.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] An enhanced electronic version, known as *ASHRAE Handbook Online* is a web-based version updated annually that contains the four latest volumes as well as extra content such as calculations, demonstration videos, and spreadsheets.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] The various versions of the Handbook are typically available to the public via technical, and other, libraries and bookstores.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] The ASHRAE Handbook has had a variety of titles.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] It began in 1922 as the **ASH&VE Guide**.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] In 1973 it became the ASHRAE Handbook, and in 1985 separate publication of inch-pound (I-P) and international system (SI) units versions of the volumes began.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] Stephen Comstock, and the Editor is Mark S.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook is published by ASHRAE from its headquarters in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook's content is created and modified by volunteers via ASHRAE's many Technical Committees (TCs), and then edited and formatted by professional staff at ASHRAE.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] For example, three chapters, in three different volumes, are maintained by TC 5.3, Room Air Distribution.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] Each chapter within a particular volume is reviewed and revised in a repeating four-year cycle; one volume is printed each year.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] In the summer of 2017 the new Fundamentals' volume was released.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] ASHRAE's Handbook Committee maintains an *Authors and Revisers Guide,* which can be obtained freely via the Handbook portion of the ASHRAE Web site.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] While each new or revised chapter manuscript is to be reviewed for technical content by each TC voting and corresponding member before publication, there are often many other pre- and post-publication reviewers.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] For example, members of the Society's Handbook Committee and the College of Fellows review chapters each year.
[src:ashrae/ashrae-handbook] Reviews, from basic comments to detailed new content, are encouraged from all users of the Handbook and may be submitted through an online commenting system.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The **American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers** (**ASHRAE** /ˈæʃreɪ/ *ASH-ray*) is an American professional association seeking to advance heating, ventilation, air conditioning and refrigeration (HVAC&R) systems design and construction.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE has over 50,000 members in more than 130 countries worldwide.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE's members comprise building services engineers, architects, mechanical contractors, building owners, equipment manufacturers' employees, and others concerned with the design and construction of HVAC&R systems in buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The society funds research projects, offers continuing education programs, and develops and publishes technical standards to improve building services engineering, energy efficiency, indoor air quality, and sustainable development.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE was founded in 1894 at a meeting of engineers in New York City, formerly headquartered at 345 East 47th Street (the United Engineering Center), and has held an annual meeting since 1895.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] Until 1954 it was known as the American Society of Heating and Ventilating Engineers (ASHVE); in that year it changed its name to the American Society of Heating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHAE).
[src:ashrae/ashrae] Its current name and organization came from the 1959 merger of ASHAE and the American Society of Refrigerating Engineers (ASRE).
[src:ashrae/ashrae] Despite having 'American' in its name, ASHRAE is a global organization, holding international events.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] In 2012, it rebranded itself with a new logo and tagline: "Shaping Tomorrow's Built Environment Today".
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The ASHRAE Handbook is a four-volume resource for HVAC&R technology and is available in both print and electronic versions.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The volumes are *Fundamentals*, *HVAC Applications*, *HVAC Systems and Equipment*, and *Refrigeration*.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] One of the four volumes is updated each year.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes a set of standards and guidelines relating to HVAC systems and issues, that are often referenced in building codes and used by consulting engineers, mechanical contractors, architects, and government agencies.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] These standards are periodically reviewed, revised and republished.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The society also publishes two magazines: the *ASHRAE Journal* is issued monthly, and *High Performing Buildings Magazine* is published quarterly.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] They contain articles on related technology, information on upcoming meetings, editorials, and case studies of various well-performing buildings.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes books, *ASHRAE Transactions*, and the *International Journal of HVAC&R Research*.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE supported the Streamlining Energy Efficiency for Schools Act of 2014 (H.R.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] 4092; 113th Congress), a bill that would require the United States Department of Energy to establish a centralized clearinghouse to disseminate information on federal programs, incentives, and mechanisms for financing energy-efficient retrofits and upgrades at schools.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE offers six categories of awards: achievement awards to recognize personal honors; personal awards for general and specific society activities; paper awards; society awards for groups or chapters; chapters and regional awards.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE Fellow is a Membership Grade of Distinction conferred by The College of Fellows of ASHRAE, Inc. to an ASHRAE member with significant publications or innovations and distinguished scientific and engineering background in the fields of heating, refrigeration, air conditioning, ventilation.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The ASHRAE Fellow membership grade is the highest elected grade in ASHRAE.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] ASHRAE has a Hall of Fame honoring "deceased members who have made milestone contributions to the growth of ASHRAE-related technology.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] To demonstrate the Society's commitment to sustainability, ASHRAE renovated its previous headquarters building in Atlanta, Ga.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] After the renovation and occupancy in June 2008, the building received many awards, including an Energy Star rating with a score of 95, a Platinum Certification from USGBC's LEED program, and four Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The current site energy use intensity (EUI) is 35.8 kBtu/Sqft (411 MJ/m2), a 60 percent reduction from the pre-renovation value.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The renovation included the use of a dedicated outdoor air supply (DOAS) system with energy recovery and humidity control; a ground-source heat pump system; and variable refrigerant flow systems with heat recovery.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] The building also serves as a live case study.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] A web-based user interface allowed researchers around the world to extract data from the building to study factors such as energy use and electric power demand, water consumption and indoor air quality.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] In 2018, ASHRAE decided to move their world headquarters, settling on retrofitting a 1970s-era building in Peachtree Corners, suburban Atlanta.
[src:ashrae/ashrae] Completed in 2022, the building has been renovated to comply with ASHRAE's own standards, including ASHRAE 90.1, and the organization has the goal of operating the building at net-zero energy, powered by a large on-site solar array.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:ashrae/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:ashrae/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:ashrae/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
